\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "par:removal-of-linearly-dependent-vector"

\end_inset

We already know that if a vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 has dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, then any subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 containing fewer than 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 elements is not a basis.
 It therefore must either be linearly dependent or not span 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 We will argue that such a set does not span 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 The statement is clearly true when the dimension of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 (there are no sets with less than 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 elements) and 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

 (only the empty set has less than one element, but the empty set does not
 span a nonempty vector space).
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq2$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\{\mathbf{u}_{1},\mathbf{u}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{u}_{p}\}$
\end_inset

 be a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $p<n$
\end_inset

 and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is a spanning set.
 Because 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 spans 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 but is not a basis, 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 must be linearly dependent.
 This is a contradiction in the case 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

 since any set with one element is linearly independent.
 In the case 
\begin_inset Formula $n>2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 contains some element that can be written as a linear combination of the
 others.
 By rearranging the order of the elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 if necessary, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}_{1}$
\end_inset

 be the element that can be written as a linear combination of the others
 and write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{u}_{1}=c_{2}\mathbf{u}_{2}+c_{3}\mathbf{u}_{3}+\cdots c_{p}\mathbf{u}_{p}.\label{eq:lin-combo-0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{S}=S\backslash\{\mathbf{u}_{1}\}=\{\mathbf{u}_{2},\mathbf{u}_{3},\ldots,\mathbf{u}_{p}\}$
\end_inset

 still spans 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

: for arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{v}=c_{1}\mathbf{u}_{1}+c_{2}\mathbf{u}_{2}+\cdots c_{p}\mathbf{u}_{p}\label{eq:lin-combo}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and substitute (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lin-combo-0"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) into (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lin-combo"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), thereby writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 as a linear combination of the elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{S}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{S}$
\end_inset

 is linearly dependent, repeat the process of removing an element that can
 be written as a linear combination of the others, and continue until the
 remaining set is linearly independent (and still spanning).
 This will happen when there is one element left, if not sooner, so the
 process is guaranteed to end.
 At this point what is left is a basis with less than 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 elements, an impossibility.
 It must be that 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is not spanning.
\end_layout

